      <div xml:id="NA227-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu varaiyātu neṭuṅ kālam vantoḻukat tōḻi talaimakaṉai varaivu muṭukac colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said to HIM so that he would conclude the marriage when he was coming for a long time without marrying.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA227">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            aṟintō raṟaṉila reṉṟal ciṟanta</l>
<l>            viṉṉuyir kaḻiyiṉu naṉiyiṉ ṉātē</l>
<l>            puṉṉaiyaṅ kāṉaṟ puṇarkuṟi vāytta</l>
<l>            piṉṉī rōtiyeṉ ṟōḻik kaṉṉō</l>
<l>            paṭumaṇi yāṉaip pacumpūṭ cōḻar </l>
<l>            koṭinuṭaṅku maṟuki ṉārkkāṭ ṭāṅkaṭ</l>
<l>            kaḷḷuṭait taṭaviṟ puḷḷolit tōvāt</l>
<l>            tērvaḻaṅku teruvi ṉaṉṉa</l>
<l>            kauvaiyā kiṉṟa taiyaniṉ ṉaruḷē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Even if [her] sweet life passes by, that was above saying</l>
<l rend="indent2">“those who know [are] not devoid of virtue,”</l>
<l rend="indent3">it is not very pleasant.</l>
<l>Alas, for my friend with braided moist hair</l>
<l rend="indent">who has reached the sign of union in the seashore grove of Puṉṉais</l>
<l>scandal has become, sir, your consideration,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[loud] as in the streets, where the chariot passes,</l>
<l rend="indent2">the birds unceasingly calling in the trees full of nectar,<note place="foot">For <term xml:lang="ta">taṭavu</term>, cf. note on KT 160.3. T.V.G. wants to take it as a large jar here, the image depicting the prosperity of the town is thus that there are pots of toddy everywhere which are swarmed by bees.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">there in Ārkkāṭu, in the streets with swaying banners,</l>
<l rend="indent">of the Cōḻa king with green ornaments, [his] elephant</l>
<l rend="indent">with a sounding bell.<note place="foot">T.V.G. explains here that the elephant has one bell fastened to each side which ring alternately with the leg moving forward.</note></l>
<lg type="alternate" sameAs="1+2b">
    <l>Even if [her] excellent life passes by, saying “the knowledgeable</l>
    <l>ones [are] not devoid of virtue,” is not very pleasant.<note place="foot">As so often with the aphorism type, the actual message of lines 1+2 is not clear, and the problem is older, as the variants on <term xml:lang="ta">eṉṟal ciṟanta</term> show. The <term xml:lang="ta">aṟintōr</term> certainly refers in a general way to HIM who should have known better than to treat HER thus, but who says that and what is the relation to the passing of her life?</note></l>
   </lg>
        </lg>
      </div>
